  <h2 class="section-heading" id="configuring-vs-code">Configuring VS Code to Recognize Custom Interfaces</h2>
  <p><strong>This is a completely optional helper step for C++ nodes.</strong> VS Code will resolve your custom paths and clear syntax indexing errors in your script editor. Code compilation works independently of this adjustment.</p>
  
  <p>The compiled header artifacts are saved under the <code>install/[package_name]/include</code> output track.</p>
  <p>Modify the <code>c_cpp_properties.json</code> file located inside your local workspace <code>.vscode</code> folder, inserting the track layout rule:</p>
  <CodeBlock code={vscodeJsonCode} lang="json" customHtml={vscodeJsonCustom} />

  <blockquote>
    <strong>NOTE:</strong> You must open VS Code directly targeted at the root or <code>src</code> path of your workspace directory tree to hook the properties configuration. Use the command sequence inside your active terminal:
  </blockquote>
  <CodeBlock code={codePeriodCode} lang="bash" />

  <p>To confirm your current path string matches your context requirements, check the output of:</p>
